&#xa0;
[normal]DDB0124[bold]Tessa [bold]Burrington[bold] – Written evidence[bold]&#xa0;[bold]JOINT COMMITTEE ON THE DRAFT DEREGULATION BILL[bold]Call for Written Evidence 15 September 2013
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Dear Sir/Madam
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Widening the debate[bold]&#xa0;[bold]I discovered by chance the invitation to comment on the Draft Deregulation Bill while looking at the Red Tape Challenge website. I was concerned to read that it was proposed that there may be a duty to promote economic growth – on a planet of finite resources – perhaps not the best idea. Of course there are no easy answers, 
[normal]but accepting the limits to growth would certainly help to appraise alternatives
[normal].  There are many different viewpoints and I would hope the debate was wider so that other viewpoints could be considered and “flaws” ironed out. The time scale for the debate should not be fixed so to speak at 3 months. It should be ongoing.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Many people, economists
[normal]8
[normal] and organisations with something important to say will be unaware of the consultation, 
[normal]such as CASSE
[normal]9
[normal] (the Centre for the Advancement of a Steady State Economy)
[normal]. The deadline should be extended and the debate ongoing.
[normal] I would like to make some general comments.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]I believe there are fundamental flaws in the concept of the red tape challenge, for example the embarrassing list of members interests on the ACRE
[normal]13
[normal] web site. 
[normal]Will the introduction of a duty to have 
[normal]regard
[normal] to “promoting economic growth” compromise the independence of regulators? What additional safeguards are required to ensure that the introduction of such a duty will not compromise the independence of a 
[normal]regulator.
[normal]  
[normal]I feel there is
[normal] no true[bold] or limited “independence” with regard to food safety regulators for example and many food sovereignty and humanitarian organisations, members of the public and NGOs are aware of this. FSA, FDA, EFSA.... revolving doors ......
[normal]  all have come under harsh criticism despite some good work in some areas.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]I disagree that there should be legislation with regard to a “
[normal]duty 
[normal]to promote economic growth”.  I would not acknowledge such legislation neither would many others.
[normal]The various view points of the individuals and organisations listed below should be taken into 
[normal]account
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Leave no stone unturned[bold]There are many other organisations and individuals that I have not listed which would be able to provide feedback and alternative view points to those proposed. Lord Heseltine and Milton Friedman are not of course the only people to have ever held an opinion, leave no stone unturned!
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Viewpoints[bold]Naomi Klein – author of The Shock Doctrine
[normal]2 
[normal]and No Logo (international best seller)
[normal]Polly Higgins – Ecocide is a crime
[normal]1
[normal], I would add to Polly’s view point that we are all responsible in one sense.
[normal]....The United Nations is to discuss, approve and promote among the Member States an International Ecocide Convention, aiming to protect the Earth and its living species and hold legally accountable institutions, organisms, organisations and their leaders.....
[normal]Via Campesina
[normal]3
